snippet.textDisplay: Macs music got me through my suicide attempts back in 2015. I used to blast weekend while I drank myself into Oblivion. After those attempts didn't succeed (obviously) I took it as a sign that i just wasn't meant to go out that way. His music guided me through the lowest lows of my life, and my heart still aches knowing he's gone. I'm not sure if im in denial or what but I still kind of refuse to believe it.

snippet.textDisplay: He's got that Ray Charles rock going on in the beginning. I love it when someone gets so into whatever song they're playing that you can basically see the music just flood their body while they're performing. Hard to believe this is the same guy that wrote Oy Vey lol not saying anything bad at all about that song, it's just wild how much of a difference there is and how versatile Mac was when it came to music. Truly one of a kind. I didn't really start listening to him until after he passed because, tbh I thought he was just another dude on the rap scene. Then I heard Self Care, Nikes On My Feet, Diablo and Stay and was hooked. Then I downloaded GO:OD AM, Swimming, and a few songs from Best Day Ever and realized how big of a mistake I made by doing the biggest thing you should never do; judge a book by its cover. Luckily though, music is forever. So even though Mac is gone and we'll never get new music, he left plenty behind that we can enjoy forever.

Then I heard Self Care, Nikes On My Feet, Diablo and Stay and was hooked. Then I downloaded GO:OD AM, Swimming, and a few songs from Best Day Ever and realized how big of a mistake I made by doing the biggest thing you should never do; judge a book by its cover. Luckily though, music is forever. So even though Mac is gone and we'll never get new music, he left plenty behind that we can enjoy forever.
RIP Mo''

snippet.textDisplay: I miss Mac so fucking much. I got to meet him on his Divine Feminine tour and he radiated nothing but love & light. He was an uncommonly kind human being, and a true artist. People with his kind of creativity are always driven insane by it. He was a gentle soul that didn’t deserve the fate he got. Swimming sounded so much like a cry for help. But this one is different, like he was in an entirely different space when making this. This album feels so much like acceptance of that fate, and that he knew that it would be his last message to everyone. He’s telling us “it’s okay” from the other side. RIP Mac, I hope you found that peace you’ve been looking for 💙 92 till infinity
